    <title>Combined summary - Changes to BIP-360 - Pay to Quantum Resistant Hash (P2QRH)</title>
    <updated>2025-07-25T03:02:27.405007+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://delvingbitcoin.org/t/changes-to-bip-360-pay-to-quantum-resistant-hash-p2qrh/1811" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The conversation delves into the complexities of enhancing Bitcoin's resilience against quantum computing threats, focusing on a proposal that amends the Pay to Quantum Resistant Hash (P2QRH) to utilize a script-only version of Taproot (P2TR). By excluding the quantum-vulnerable key-spend pathway, this revision aims to bolster security measures against potential quantum attacks. The proposed changes detail how P2QRH outputs are to be directly committed to the tapleaf merkle root, calculated by taproot, thus leveraging existing infrastructure for better integration while enhancing protection from long-exposure attacks anticipated to precede short-exposure ones. This approach proposes a significant shift from previous strategies by offering an alternative to the disabling of key-spends in P2TR upon the emergence of viable quantum threats, termed Q-Day. It emphasizes a proactive, rather than reactive, adjustment to the ecosystem, providing a buffer against urgent consensus changes driven by immediate threats.

Moreover, the discussion highlights a strategic decoupling of Post-Quantum (PQ) signatures from BIP-360, allowing these elements to be refined independently. This separation is pivotal, as it avoids early commitments to specific PQ signature algorithms and ensures flexibility in adapting to future quantum-resistant cryptographic methods. The proposal includes an informational section that envisages the incorporation of tapscript PQ signature verification opcodes for ML-DSA (CRYSTALS-Dilithium) and SLH-DSA (SPHINCS+) through OP_SUCCESSx opcodes. This foresight facilitates a framework that could activate PQ signature algorithms separately when deemed necessary, laying a foundation for the integration of new signature algorithms without requiring updates to the tapleaf versions. An upcoming BIP is expected to provide a detailed specification for these PQ signatures, contributing to the ongoing efforts to fortify the Bitcoin protocol against emerging quantum computing capabilities.</summary>
